- I don't know why
you would start working on

10:33.925 --> 10:36.928
something else with an hour
left in this competition.

10:36.928 --> 10:37.929
[tool grinding]

10:40.956 --> 10:41.724
What the heck is

10:41.724 --> 10:43.643
happening right now?

10:43.643 --> 10:45.603
- Did Daniel abandon
his blade?

10:45.603 --> 10:48.314
- The last thing on the planet
that I want to do right now

10:48.314 --> 10:50.108
is start all over again.

10:50.108 --> 10:51.943
- I don't know why
you would start working on

10:51.943 --> 10:55.071
something else with an hour
left in this competition.

10:55.071 --> 10:57.365
<i>- I have no options.</i>
<i>I have to start over.</i>

10:57.365 --> 10:59.951
<i>I got a long ways to go and</i>
<i>a short time to get there.</i>

10:59.951 --> 11:02.537
I'm gonna do everything
I can to catch up.

11:02.537 --> 11:04.997
That just shattered like glass
when I hardened it.

11:04.997 --> 11:06.999
I'm starting over.

11:06.999 --> 11:09.794
- So, Daniel with a little over
an hour left on the clock.

11:09.794 --> 11:12.672
He's gotta forge weld
two pieces of steel together,

11:12.672 --> 11:15.299
and he's gotta make his blade.

11:15.299 --> 11:16.634
- Wow.

11:16.634 --> 11:19.262
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

11:19.262 --> 11:21.389
- The way I'm feeling,
I want to puke right now.

11:21.389 --> 11:23.141
I don't know what
this blade's gonna do.

11:23.141 --> 11:25.017
I don't know
if it's gonna shatter

11:25.017 --> 11:26.144
when I put it in this oil.

11:26.144 --> 11:27.103
And here we go.

11:27.103 --> 11:29.230
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:29.230 --> 11:30.982
- All right,
Bob is in the quench oil.

11:30.982 --> 11:33.359
- No thermocycling.
- No thermocycling.

11:33.359 --> 11:36.404
- Hopefully, he's gonna find
grain in there somehow.

11:36.404 --> 11:38.489
<i>- I don't hear any pings.</i>

11:38.489 --> 11:40.074
I let it get cooled down
enough, I pull it out.

11:40.074 --> 11:41.576
I have no warp.

11:41.576 --> 11:43.536
We are golden.
All right.

11:43.536 --> 11:45.496
I make knives the same reason
people drink beer:

11:45.496 --> 11:46.455
they like to do it.

11:46.455 --> 11:48.166
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:48.166 --> 11:49.500
It works.

11:49.500 --> 11:51.586
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:51.586 --> 11:54.130
- So, Collin has lost
his work stake,

11:54.130 --> 11:56.716
and is now working with just
tongs over there on big blue.

11:56.716 --> 11:58.634
- Oh, metal on the floor.

11:58.634 --> 12:00.469
<i>- You gotta be like</i>
<i>a phoenix out here.</i>

12:00.469 --> 12:02.096
<i>You know,</i>
<i>sometimes you get broken,</i>

12:02.096 --> 12:03.472
<i>but you gotta rise up.</i>

12:03.472 --> 12:04.682
You don't want
to be in the ash.

12:04.682 --> 12:06.934
You wanna be a majestic bird.

12:06.934 --> 12:10.563
So, it's time to--it's time
to shake off that ash.

12:10.563 --> 12:12.648
<i>It's time to</i>
<i>be forged in fire.</i>

12:12.648 --> 12:14.483
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:14.483 --> 12:15.735
So after that pep talk,
I still don't know

12:15.735 --> 12:17.069
what the [bleep]
I'm gonna do.

12:17.069 --> 12:19.030
- Looks good.
You're doing it.

12:19.030 --> 12:21.532
- I guess, just gonna grind it
into the shape of a blade.

12:21.532 --> 12:23.910
You can roll your eyes,
you can be ashamed,

12:23.910 --> 12:26.078
but I gotta have a blade.

12:26.078 --> 12:27.622
If I can get the profile in,

12:27.622 --> 12:29.040
<i>I can heat treat it,</i>
<i>get it quenched.</i>

12:29.040 --> 12:30.666
- 30 minutes!

12:30.666 --> 12:32.585
- Give them
the old razzle dazzle!

12:32.585 --> 12:34.462
<i>We got the fire coming out.</i>

12:34.462 --> 12:36.297
Everybody's like, "Oh,
what's happening over here?"

12:36.297 --> 12:37.965
Whoo!

12:37.965 --> 12:39.050
<i>Like,</i>
<i>you know what's happening.</i>

12:39.050 --> 12:40.760
Forging in fire out here.

12:40.760 --> 12:42.887
<i>I love it.</i>
<i>It's great.</i>

12:42.887 --> 12:43.763
Whoo!
All right.

12:43.763 --> 12:45.932
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:45.932 --> 12:47.975
- Damn.

12:47.975 --> 12:50.269
Did anybody see where
my mild steel has gone?

12:50.269 --> 12:55.024
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:55.024 --> 12:56.859
I found it.

12:56.859 --> 12:58.653
<i>So, I've left</i>
<i>this mild steel to the end.</i>

12:58.653 --> 13:02.406
<i>And I realize working on</i>
<i>my billet took me so long,</i>

13:02.406 --> 13:04.033
that it may cost me.

13:04.033 --> 13:05.368
<i>I could have</i>
<i>a functional knife,</i>

13:05.368 --> 13:06.827
but if I don't integrate
this mild steel,

13:06.827 --> 13:08.412
I'm going home, and that's it.

13:08.412 --> 13:10.706
- Wow,
that's quite a cross guard.

13:10.706 --> 13:13.042
Oh, oh, no, that's not
gonna fit in the forge.

13:13.042 --> 13:14.835
- If this mild steel
does not stick,

13:14.835 --> 13:16.712
I have not fulfilled
the parameters,

13:16.712 --> 13:18.631
I have not joined it with
the high carbon steel,

13:18.631 --> 13:20.758
and I'll be disqualified.

13:20.758 --> 13:22.843
- 20 minutes!

13:22.843 --> 13:25.263
- This second blade
isn't nearly as refined

13:25.263 --> 13:27.932
<i>as the first one, but if I can</i>
<i>get this thing quenched</i>

13:27.932 --> 13:30.518
and get to the grinder for at
least three or four minutes,

13:30.518 --> 13:32.019
<i>I'll feel like</i>
<i>I might have a chance</i>

13:32.019 --> 13:33.562
to make it through
to the second round.

13:33.562 --> 13:35.231
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:35.231 --> 13:36.857
<i>It's not as hard</i>
<i>as I want it to be,</i>

13:36.857 --> 13:39.527
but not every tool steel
is as hard as a file.

13:39.527 --> 13:42.071
<i>So, we're moving on</i>
<i>to the grinder.</i>

13:42.071 --> 13:45.741
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:45.741 --> 13:47.702
- Jesse still has
yet to quench.

13:47.702 --> 13:49.203
<i>- The guide looks awful.</i>

13:49.203 --> 13:51.789
<i>It's just this fused wreck.</i>

13:51.789 --> 13:53.457
<i>You can't even see</i>
<i>what's what.</i>

13:53.457 --> 13:54.875
- 15 seconds!

13:54.875 --> 13:56.794
<i>- I need to quench my blade.</i>

13:56.794 --> 13:58.337
- Ten! Nine!

13:58.337 --> 13:59.505
Eight!

13:59.505 --> 14:00.631
Seven!

14:00.631 --> 14:02.299
Six!
Five!

14:02.299 --> 14:03.467
Four!

14:03.467 --> 14:05.261
Three!
Two!

14:05.261 --> 14:06.762
One!

14:06.762 --> 14:07.930
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines,

14:07.930 --> 14:09.140
drop your tools!

14:09.140 --> 14:10.683
This forging round is over!

14:10.683 --> 14:13.227
[applause]

14:13.227 --> 14:16.897
<i>- I definitely royally</i>
<i>screwed up the first blade.</i>

14:16.897 --> 14:20.568
But I am happy
that I didn't give up.

14:20.568 --> 14:22.987
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:22.987 --> 14:25.239
- Bladesmiths, in this first
round of competition,

14:25.239 --> 14:26.991
each of you had to source steel

14:26.991 --> 14:28.743
from two different
locations on a cannon.

14:28.743 --> 14:30.244
It's time for the judges

14:30.244 --> 14:31.412
to take a closer look
at your work.

14:31.412 --> 14:32.997
Bob, you're up first.

14:32.997 --> 14:34.457
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:34.457 --> 14:39.712
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:39.712 --> 14:42.298
- Well, Bob, you turned in
a nice, clean piece of steel.

14:42.298 --> 14:43.799
I don't see any problems
with cracking.

14:43.799 --> 14:45.176
It's nice and straight.

14:45.176 --> 14:46.552
<i>I like the shape</i>
<i>of your handle.</i>

14:46.552 --> 14:48.054
<i>But it's kind of thick.</i>

14:48.054 --> 14:49.388
You know, if you move on
to the next round,

14:49.388 --> 14:50.639
that can be dealt with
pretty easily.

14:50.639 --> 14:52.266
Well done.
- Thank you.

14:52.266 --> 14:53.726
- All right, Daniel,

14:53.726 --> 14:55.102
please present your blade
to the judges.

14:55.102 --> 14:56.896
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:56.896 --> 14:59.899
<i>- This was really smart,</i>
<i>fast work.</i>

14:59.899 --> 15:01.942
I would love to see
that fitted up better,

15:01.942 --> 15:03.611
<i>but you hammered this out</i>
<i>and got this done</i>

15:03.611 --> 15:05.529
in basically half the time.

15:05.529 --> 15:07.490
<i>And you've got just enough</i>
<i>of a tang here</i>

15:07.490 --> 15:09.325
<i>for a blade this size.</i>

15:09.325 --> 15:11.202
So, seeing how you're
gonna connect the handle,

15:11.202 --> 15:13.245
work it into this blade
and work it into that guard,

15:13.245 --> 15:14.830
it's gonna be interesting.

15:14.830 --> 15:17.083
Good job.
- Thank you very much, sir.

15:17.083 --> 15:18.667
- Jesse, you're up next.

15:18.667 --> 15:20.878
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:20.878 --> 15:23.756
<i>- Well, Jesse, you started</i>
<i>with a huge piece of steel.</i>

15:23.756 --> 15:25.549
<i>I think it really hindered you</i>

15:25.549 --> 15:27.176
<i>and your ability</i>
<i>to get things moving.</i>

15:27.176 --> 15:30.137
The handle is kind of big
in all dimensions.

15:30.137 --> 15:32.056
<i>I like that</i>
<i>you designed a chopper,</i>

15:32.056 --> 15:34.308
but it is quite rough.
I mean, it's still rectangular.

15:34.308 --> 15:35.976
Despite all of it,
you turned something in,

15:35.976 --> 15:37.812
and it meets the parameter.
- Thank you.

15:37.812 --> 15:39.438
- Collin, you're up.

15:39.438 --> 15:41.482
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:41.482 --> 15:43.984
<i>- That kind of drop</i>
<i>to the handle,</i>

15:43.984 --> 15:46.153
<i>I mean, it'll be interesting</i>
<i>moving forward</i>

15:46.153 --> 15:48.447
to see how you're gonna deal
with this whole section

15:48.447 --> 15:50.449
and incorporate
it into a handle.

15:50.449 --> 15:52.535
As far as the blade shape goes,
it's mostly refining.

15:52.535 --> 15:54.578
Taking some of
that weight out of there.

15:54.578 --> 15:56.705
But the big question is, what
are you going to do back here?

15:56.705 --> 15:57.790
Good job.

15:57.790 --> 15:59.500
- Thank you, sir.

15:59.500 --> 16:01.335
- All right, bladesmiths.

16:01.335 --> 16:02.837
The judges have
a final decision to make

16:02.837 --> 16:04.880
about who moves on
into the next round,

16:04.880 --> 16:07.133
which means they need
to go into deliberations.

16:07.133 --> 16:08.509
So, while they do that,
I'm gonna have you

16:08.509 --> 16:10.261
leave your blades
on this table

16:10.261 --> 16:11.887
and step off The Forge floor.

16:11.887 --> 16:17.309
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:17.309 --> 16:18.811
- [sighs]

16:18.811 --> 16:20.354
- Good times, huh, guys?
- Mm.

16:20.354 --> 16:22.231
- [laughs]

16:22.231 --> 16:23.691
- Our bladesmiths
have turned in their weapons.

16:23.691 --> 16:25.109
Let's take a closer look at
the details.

16:25.109 --> 16:26.402
We'll start with Bob.

16:26.402 --> 16:28.779
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:28.779 --> 16:31.323
<i>- Nice profile.</i>
<i>Looks like a nice chopper.</i>

16:31.323 --> 16:33.117
<i>I mean, it's nice to know</i>
<i>that you can put two metals</i>

16:33.117 --> 16:34.785
and make it work.

16:34.785 --> 16:36.120
He has one piece over here,
another piece,

16:36.120 --> 16:37.204
and they came together
right here.

16:37.204 --> 16:38.747
It feels good already.

16:38.747 --> 16:40.416
- I like that curve.
I'm kind of jealous.

16:40.416 --> 16:42.126
Should've put a curve in mine,
I feel like.

16:42.126 --> 16:44.879
- Yeah, I meant to do that.
Sure.

16:44.879 --> 16:46.088
- Let's move on
to our next bladesmith.

16:46.088 --> 16:47.423
And that is Daniel.

16:47.423 --> 16:49.216
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:49.216 --> 16:51.635
<i>- He's got just enough</i>
<i>tang here</i>

16:51.635 --> 16:53.387
to make a handle work.

16:53.387 --> 16:54.972
But I think once he takes
some of the material

16:54.972 --> 16:56.432
out of this blade,
it'll make a good chopper.

16:56.432 --> 16:58.058
I mean, it's a good shape.

16:58.058 --> 16:59.685
- For a 30-minute blade,
it ain't bad, I guess.

16:59.685 --> 17:01.353
- All right, let's move on to
our next bladesmith,

17:01.353 --> 17:03.397
and that is Jesse.

17:03.397 --> 17:04.940
<i>- This thing weighs a ton.</i>

17:04.940 --> 17:06.233
<i>I mean,</i>
<i>there's a lot of steel here.</i>

17:06.233 --> 17:07.693
<i>It is perfectly rectangular.</i>

17:07.693 --> 17:09.028
<i>It's as if</i>
<i>it were a bar stock.</i>

17:09.028 --> 17:10.613
The welding is very rough,

17:10.613 --> 17:12.615
and the guard itself
is shaped poorly.

17:12.615 --> 17:14.283
I can't get my finger
underneath it,

17:14.283 --> 17:16.410
and the handle is huge.

17:16.410 --> 17:19.705
But, you know, gotta commend
him for turning something in.

17:19.705 --> 17:23.334
- All right, moving on to
our last bladesmith, Collin.

17:23.334 --> 17:25.628
- At the spine,
there is a slight warp.

17:25.628 --> 17:27.504
The pieces of mild
he put on the side,

17:27.504 --> 17:29.381
<i>you can still see the welds,</i>
<i>but hopefully</i>

17:29.381 --> 17:31.091
<i>with some refining and</i>
<i>grinding, those will go away,</i>

17:31.091 --> 17:32.760
<i>and it'll look better.</i>

17:32.760 --> 17:34.720
My big issue is this handle.
It's just tiny.

17:34.720 --> 17:36.972
- Ugh, they're looking
at the handle.

17:36.972 --> 17:38.557
- Judges, have you made
your final decision?

17:38.557 --> 17:39.558
- Yes, I have.
- Dave?

17:39.558 --> 17:41.227
- Yep.
- Ben?

17:41.227 --> 17:42.061
- Yeah.
- Let's go tell our smiths.

17:42.061 --> 17:44.146
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:44.146 --> 17:46.315
Bladesmiths, the judges have
completed their deliberation,

17:46.315 --> 17:47.900
and they've made
a final decision.

17:47.900 --> 17:49.652
The bladesmith
leaving The Forge...

17:49.652 --> 17:53.906
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:53.906 --> 17:55.407
Jesse.

17:55.407 --> 17:56.992
Your blade did not
make the cut.

17:56.992 --> 17:59.203
Doug Marcaida
is gonna tell you why.

17:59.203 --> 18:01.997
- Jesse, I hope you take from
this experience to continue on,

18:01.997 --> 18:04.208
because the world awaits
your work.

18:04.208 --> 18:06.502
But at the end of the day, your
blade was the least finished.

18:06.502 --> 18:08.295
And that's the reason
we're sending you home.

18:08.295 --> 18:10.005
- Jesse,
please surrender your blade.

18:10.005 --> 18:12.174
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:12.174 --> 18:14.552
<i>- Of the four blades,</i>
<i>mine was the most unfinished.</i>

18:14.552 --> 18:17.012
<i>The big lesson that I learned</i>
<i>here is time management.</i>

18:17.012 --> 18:19.848
Don't give up, but don't cling
to that sinking ship.

18:19.848 --> 18:22.810
I mean, I grabbed 15 pounds
of steel when I needed three.

18:22.810 --> 18:24.937
<i>My inexperience</i>
<i>was my downfall.</i>

18:24.937 --> 18:26.564
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:26.564 --> 18:28.148
- All right, bladesmiths,

18:28.148 --> 18:29.984
you've made it into
the second round.

18:29.984 --> 18:32.194
Good job, but now that
your blade's been tempered,

18:32.194 --> 18:34.280
it's time to take them
and turn them into weapons

18:34.280 --> 18:36.448
by attaching handles to them.

18:36.448 --> 18:38.742
You'll also have three hours
in which to complete your work.

18:38.742 --> 18:40.953
Keep in mind that,
when the time runs out,

18:40.953 --> 18:43.289
your blades will be tested
for strength and durability

18:43.289 --> 18:46.500
in a wooden ramrod chop.

18:46.500 --> 18:50.838
And for sharpness
in a cannon fuse slice.

18:50.838 --> 18:53.549
Good luck.
Your three hours starts now.

18:53.549 --> 18:56.927
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:56.927 --> 18:58.470
- So, I'm nervous.
I'm running over to the pantry,

18:58.470 --> 18:59.972
I don't know
what I'm gonna find,

18:59.972 --> 19:01.890
I'm looking around,
and then boom.

19:01.890 --> 19:03.892
<i>Right in front of my face,</i>
<i>a big block of canarywood.</i>

19:03.892 --> 19:05.936
And that's perfect.

19:05.936 --> 19:08.480
<i>But if I can't find</i>
<i>a way to extend this handle,</i>

19:08.480 --> 19:10.357
that's it, game over.

19:10.357 --> 19:13.152
<i>Then I look up</i>
<i>on the pantry: canisters.</i>

19:13.152 --> 19:14.737
You know what canisters have?

19:14.737 --> 19:16.697
Little lids,
and you know what that is?

19:16.697 --> 19:18.324
<i>Flat stock mild steel.</i>

19:18.324 --> 19:20.159
<i>Exactly what</i>
<i>I was looking for.</i>

19:20.159 --> 19:21.660
Boom, baby!
Yeah.

19:21.660 --> 19:24.622
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:24.622 --> 19:26.874
- I feel like
I made a pretty major flop

19:26.874 --> 19:28.584
out of the first round.

19:28.584 --> 19:30.628
<i>My hand guard does</i>
<i>not look good.</i>

19:30.628 --> 19:33.464
So, I'm gonna do everything
that I can to redeem myself.

19:33.464 --> 19:35.674
I'm gonna make my handle
out of birdseye maple,

19:35.674 --> 19:37.259
because
I'm very familiar with it,

19:37.259 --> 19:39.219
and my strategy is to
get the handle on

19:39.219 --> 19:41.180
as quickly as possible,

19:41.180 --> 19:43.891
'cause I've got a lot of
grinding to do on this blade.

19:43.891 --> 19:46.852
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:46.852 --> 19:48.520
<i>- It feels really good</i>
<i>to be going to round two.</i>

19:48.520 --> 19:50.648
It's better than being
eliminated in round one.

19:50.648 --> 19:52.191
I have the issues
that I need to address,

19:52.191 --> 19:53.859
and I have
a really good game plan.

19:53.859 --> 19:55.527
<i>I need to grind</i>
<i>the handle a little bit.</i>

19:55.527 --> 19:57.488
I need to put a handle on.

19:57.488 --> 19:59.323
<i>After that, I'm going to</i>
<i>start grinding the edge.</i>

19:59.323 --> 20:01.742
I'm gonna get it down to where
I have a good foundation

20:01.742 --> 20:03.577
to start putting a sharp edge,

20:03.577 --> 20:06.413
and I really don't think
it's gonna take me three hours.

20:06.413 --> 20:09.500
- All right, so, Bob brought
some Paracord to the table.

20:09.500 --> 20:10.959
- Bob is a military man.

20:10.959 --> 20:12.711
He can make an airplane
out of Paracord.

20:12.711 --> 20:14.672
- I spent most of
my military career

20:14.672 --> 20:16.507
in Asia
and in the Philippines.

20:16.507 --> 20:19.093
<i>And one of the materials</i>
<i>I did use was Paracord.</i>

20:19.093 --> 20:21.512
If done right,
it is a good handle, it holds.

20:21.512 --> 20:24.139
- I could do a cord wrap
that'll kink your boots, man.

20:24.139 --> 20:25.182
- That a thing?

20:25.182 --> 20:26.850
- [laughs]

20:26.850 --> 20:28.811
<i>- So, I have my canister lids.</i>

20:28.811 --> 20:30.979
<i>I gotta weld them</i>
<i>on the back of the tang.</i>

20:30.979 --> 20:32.856
Just go real nice
and easy, slow,

20:32.856 --> 20:34.858
<i>make those MIG welds deep,</i>

20:34.858 --> 20:37.027
<i>and I can't risk this</i>
<i>falling apart, no matter what.</i>

20:37.027 --> 20:38.529
- I hope he's paying
attention to the heat

20:38.529 --> 20:40.739
and how it's travelling.

20:40.739 --> 20:43.325
Because that's a long
weld he's doing right there.

20:43.325 --> 20:44.535
- But it's all on the tang,
right?

20:44.535 --> 20:46.453
So he should be fine.

20:46.453 --> 20:48.831
- The tang can go right down
to the blade, you know?

20:48.831 --> 20:51.250
Tang bone's connected
to the blade bone.

20:51.250 --> 20:53.544
- It's a little wonky.

20:53.544 --> 20:55.295
<i>- What is going on</i>
<i>with this grinder?</i>

20:55.295 --> 20:58.424
It should take off metal
like crazy--it's not.

20:58.424 --> 21:01.093
- Bob's got
his grinder running at 40%.

21:01.093 --> 21:02.553
- Yeah, that's pretty slow.
- Maybe.

21:02.553 --> 21:04.388
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:04.388 --> 21:06.557
- He's got a runaway belt.

21:06.557 --> 21:08.851
- He's got the back half of
the belt hanging off the wheel.

21:08.851 --> 21:10.769
- Bob's grinder
has gone haywire.

21:10.769 --> 21:12.271
It's on the fritz.

21:12.271 --> 21:14.022
- I'm trying to get belts
on this grinder.

21:14.022 --> 21:15.774
<i>It's throwing them like</i>
<i>a horse at a bad rodeo.</i>

21:15.774 --> 21:17.151
If I don't get
this grinder to work,

21:17.151 --> 21:18.986
I am in trouble.
I'm going home.

21:18.986 --> 21:20.654
- How long do you think
Bob's gonna sit here

21:20.654 --> 21:22.531
and try to fix
that one grinder?

21:22.531 --> 21:25.325
- There are other grinders.
Let go, let it go!

21:25.325 --> 21:28.120
- If Bob gets put out
after this round,

21:28.120 --> 21:29.455
there is no coming back.

21:29.455 --> 21:30.169
- Hurry up, Bob!

21:32.736 --> 21:34.654
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:34.654 --> 21:37.240
- If Bob gets put out
after this round,

21:37.240 --> 21:38.784
there is no coming back.

21:38.784 --> 21:40.327
- Hurry up, Bob!

21:40.327 --> 21:42.162
- It never occurred to me
until right then

21:42.162 --> 21:44.289
to look at and check the speed
control on the grinder.

21:44.289 --> 21:46.166
Who turned the...

21:47.375 --> 21:49.461
I know I had that
higher than 20.

21:49.461 --> 21:53.048
- Bob finally has found
second gear on the grinder.

21:53.048 --> 21:54.591
- Hey, that works a little
better, look at that.

21:54.591 --> 21:56.384
At home I have
a much smaller grinder,

21:56.384 --> 21:57.844
and I've never used one
this size.

21:57.844 --> 21:59.638
<i>This thing is a beast.</i>

21:59.638 --> 22:02.224
- Bob got it cranked up,
and he's hogging away metal,

22:02.224 --> 22:05.310
working on his blade's
overall profile.

22:05.310 --> 22:07.103
<i>- I checked the edge,</i>
<i>I checked everything.</i>

22:07.103 --> 22:09.064
It is a working blade.
Everything was good.

22:09.064 --> 22:11.399
<i>Anything else I do just</i>
<i>to kind of make it pretty...</i>

22:11.399 --> 22:12.734
And she's finished.

22:12.734 --> 22:14.361
Could jeopardize it.

22:14.361 --> 22:16.279
- So, Bob has just
grabbed an apple box.

22:16.279 --> 22:19.616
- Well,
that's an interesting plan.

22:19.616 --> 22:22.410
- What are you doing?
- I'm done.

22:22.410 --> 22:23.745
<i>I feel confident</i>
<i>that this blade</i>

22:23.745 --> 22:25.497
is going to excel
in the tests.

22:25.497 --> 22:27.958
And I believe it's going to
beat my competitors out.

22:27.958 --> 22:30.001
- We've got an hour
and five minutes left

22:30.001 --> 22:32.796
in this round of competition
and Bob is saying he's done.

22:32.796 --> 22:35.090
- Now'd be the time to chop
on that wooden block.

22:35.090 --> 22:36.675
- See how your edge holds up.

22:36.675 --> 22:38.301
- Make sure everything
is high and tight

22:38.301 --> 22:39.886
rather than sit there
and just let it be.

22:39.886 --> 22:42.055
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:42.055 --> 22:44.015
<i>- So, I'm rocking along,</i>
<i>working on my blade,</i>

22:44.015 --> 22:46.017
<i>and I hear Bob say...</i>
- I'm done.

22:46.017 --> 22:48.311
- He sets his blade on
his anvil and he sits down.

22:48.311 --> 22:50.021
I don't know what's going on.

22:50.021 --> 22:52.440
You ain't right on the head.
- You knew that.

22:52.440 --> 22:54.276
<i>- So, here I am working,</i>

22:54.276 --> 22:56.987
and then I get a tap on
the shoulder, and it's Bob.

22:56.987 --> 22:59.990
- Bob has switched over
to psychological warfare,

22:59.990 --> 23:01.867
using distraction techniques.

23:01.867 --> 23:03.076
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:03.076 --> 23:04.828
- Have you seen the blade

23:04.828 --> 23:06.621
that Daniel's working on
right now,

23:06.621 --> 23:08.498
where he's leaving
the hammer marks?

23:08.498 --> 23:10.166
When you look at it,
it looks like

23:10.166 --> 23:11.668
perfect thumbprints
all the way--

23:11.668 --> 23:13.044
- Yes.
- It's so symmetrical.

23:13.044 --> 23:14.629
- It looks so good, right?

23:14.629 --> 23:16.339
- I am leaving the forge scale

23:16.339 --> 23:18.592
on about the top inch
of the blade.

23:18.592 --> 23:21.052
I feel like it adds
cosmetically to the primitive,

23:21.052 --> 23:22.846
traditional style of the bowie.

23:22.846 --> 23:24.222
<i>So I'm going for it.</i>

23:24.222 --> 23:25.724
- Daniel's blade,
it's scaring me.

23:25.724 --> 23:28.143
This guy's good,
and it's got me worried.

23:28.143 --> 23:30.228
<i>My knife weighs a ton,</i>
<i>it's unwieldy.</i>

23:30.228 --> 23:32.272
<i>So, I've got to grind.</i>

23:32.272 --> 23:34.149
♪ Grind, grind, grind it off,
grind it off, baby ♪

23:34.149 --> 23:36.276
♪ Start grinding
feeling good ♪

23:36.276 --> 23:38.653
♪ Grinding it off
ah-ah-ah ♪

23:38.653 --> 23:39.696
- Two minutes, bladesmiths.

23:39.696 --> 23:41.615
[grinder whirring]

23:41.615 --> 23:42.824
- That's a grinding style
you don't see very often.

23:42.824 --> 23:44.618
- No.
- [laughs]

23:44.618 --> 23:46.620
- Some of that bump and grind.
- Yeah, really.

23:46.620 --> 23:49.414
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:49.414 --> 23:51.875
- Ten...nine...eight...

23:51.875 --> 23:53.293
- Hurry, Bob.
- Seven...

23:53.293 --> 23:57.213
six...five...four...three...

23:57.213 --> 24:00.634
two...one.

24:00.634 --> 24:04.054
Bladesmiths, this second round
of competition is over.

24:04.054 --> 24:05.805
- The tests are next.

24:05.805 --> 24:09.434
I'm confident that
my knife is gonna do good,

24:09.434 --> 24:12.771
but I was confident that the
first blade was gonna do good,

24:12.771 --> 24:15.690
and that thing cracked
into a million freaking pieces.

24:15.690 --> 24:18.109
- Bladesmiths,
this is the strength test.

24:18.109 --> 24:20.320
The wooden ramrod chop.

24:20.320 --> 24:22.364
To test the strength and
durability of your edge,

24:22.364 --> 24:24.407
as well as the overall
construction of your knives,

24:24.407 --> 24:26.493
I'll be chopping
into this ramrod ten times.

24:26.493 --> 24:27.869
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:27.869 --> 24:29.287
Bob, you're up first.
Are you ready?

24:29.287 --> 24:31.289
- No, but let's do it.
- All right.

24:31.289 --> 24:33.667
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:33.667 --> 24:35.377
<i>- Naturally, I'm nervous.</i>

24:35.377 --> 24:37.295
<i>My concern on the wooden</i>
<i>ramrod chop</i>

24:37.295 --> 24:39.547
<i>is that the edge rolls or</i>
<i>maybe the blade breaks.</i>

24:39.547 --> 24:41.132
<i>Steel is a finicky</i>
<i>little critter.</i>

24:41.132 --> 24:42.801
<i>Sometimes it works real good,</i>

24:42.801 --> 24:44.761
<i>sometimes it just</i>
<i>snaps in your face.</i>

24:44.761 --> 24:46.680
You'll never know
until you test it.

24:46.680 --> 24:52.519
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:52.519 --> 24:53.812
And there she goes.

24:53.812 --> 24:55.939
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:55.939 --> 24:57.023
Feel like a punch in the gut.

24:57.023 --> 24:58.858
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:58.858 --> 25:00.527
- Well, Bob, quite obviously,
your blade broke.

25:00.527 --> 25:01.611
- Oops.

25:01.611 --> 25:03.154
- Looking at your grain,

25:03.154 --> 25:04.698
I would like
to have seen thermocycling

25:04.698 --> 25:06.866
done to your blade.

25:06.866 --> 25:08.576
<i>The grain that I'm seeing in</i>
<i>here is a lot more coarse</i>

25:08.576 --> 25:09.911
<i>than I would like to see.</i>

25:09.911 --> 25:11.788
And that lends
to a more brittle blade.

25:11.788 --> 25:14.833
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:14.833 --> 25:17.127
- Bob, your blade suffered
a critical failure

25:17.127 --> 25:19.629
the very first strike
of the very first test.

25:19.629 --> 25:22.340
However, in order to proceed,

25:22.340 --> 25:25.427
two more bladesmiths still have
to make it through this test.

25:25.427 --> 25:27.804
Bob, you're not out yet.

25:27.804 --> 25:31.099
Gentlemen, your blades are made
out of the exact same steel.

25:31.099 --> 25:33.476
Let's see if they hold up.

25:33.476 --> 25:35.270
Ben?

25:35.270 --> 25:36.980
- Daniel, you're up next.
You feeling lucky?

25:36.980 --> 25:39.190
- I reckon so.
- All right.

25:39.190 --> 25:43.737
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:43.737 --> 25:46.698
<i>- Everything about the steel</i>
<i>in my blade and in Bob's blade</i>

25:46.698 --> 25:48.366
is identical.

25:48.366 --> 25:50.493
<i>The thing that</i>
<i>scares me right now</i>

25:50.493 --> 25:52.495
<i>is if I got</i>
<i>this thing too hard,</i>

25:52.495 --> 25:54.122
the first time
he hits that ramrod,

25:54.122 --> 25:56.041
it's gonna shatter like glass.

25:56.041 --> 26:02.922
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:07.761 --> 26:11.514
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:11.514 --> 26:13.808
- Well, Daniel,
it held up very well.

26:13.808 --> 26:16.519
The edge is just not quite
as sharp as it was before.

26:16.519 --> 26:18.396
But there's no rolls,
there's no chipping.

26:18.396 --> 26:19.981
This was impressive
to watch you do.

26:19.981 --> 26:21.649
This is your second blade.
- Thank you, sir.

26:21.649 --> 26:23.234
- Collin, you're up.
You ready?

26:23.234 --> 26:24.861
- I'm jealous.
I want to swing it.

26:24.861 --> 26:25.820
[laughs]

26:25.820 --> 26:27.739
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:27.739 --> 26:29.866
<i>Uh, I'm feeling for Bob.</i>

26:29.866 --> 26:32.243
But I made my knife
the same way.

26:32.243 --> 26:33.995
<i>I don't know</i>
<i>what's gonna happen.</i>

26:33.995 --> 26:36.122
<i>I'm kind of freaking out</i>
<i>a little bit.</i>

26:36.122 --> 26:36.843
Swing away.

26:36.843 --> 26:37.307
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:39.492 --> 26:40.347
- Collin, you're up.
You ready?

26:40.347 --> 26:41.014
- I'm jealous.
I want to swing it.

26:41.014 --> 26:42.098
[laughs]

26:42.098 --> 26:45.644
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

26:45.644 --> 26:47.270
<i>And I'm just like...</i>

26:47.270 --> 26:50.774
Oh, [bleep].

26:50.774 --> 26:52.317
You can't look away.
It's like a car wreck.

26:52.317 --> 26:55.111
You just lock in.

26:55.111 --> 27:01.868
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:03.662 --> 27:07.165
[bleep].

27:07.165 --> 27:10.043
Well,
we're in the same camp now.

27:10.043 --> 27:16.091
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:16.091 --> 27:19.594
- Well, Collin,
the knife broke, obviously.

27:19.594 --> 27:21.971
<i>The grain structure in here</i>
<i>is sort of in-between.</i>

27:21.971 --> 27:23.765
<i>It's not quite</i>
<i>as coarse as I've seen,</i>

27:23.765 --> 27:26.476
but it's certainly not the
finest grain I've ever seen.

27:26.476 --> 27:29.062
The thing that's really telling
is, there was a MIG weld

27:29.062 --> 27:30.522
that went across here to hold

27:30.522 --> 27:31.981
this piece of
mild steel on the side.

27:31.981 --> 27:34.234
Right next to it,
there's this bronze line,

27:34.234 --> 27:36.528
and what that tells me is that

27:36.528 --> 27:38.822
<i>there was a surface crack</i>
<i>there before the heat treat.</i>

27:38.822 --> 27:40.824
That's why it broke
where it broke.

27:40.824 --> 27:41.783
- Mm.

27:41.783 --> 27:46.037
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:46.037 --> 27:48.039
- Daniel, you'll be moving on
to the final round.

27:48.039 --> 27:49.582
Congratulations.

27:49.582 --> 27:52.460
Collin, Bob,
both of your blades

27:52.460 --> 27:56.005
suffered catastrophic failures
in our strength test.

27:56.005 --> 27:58.925
Collin, your blade
lasted longer than Bob.

27:58.925 --> 28:02.220
Bob, your blade suffered that
catastrophic failure

28:02.220 --> 28:04.389
in one stroke.
And for that reason,

28:04.389 --> 28:06.224
I have to ask you
to please leave The Forge.

28:06.224 --> 28:10.061
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:10.061 --> 28:11.771
<i>- If you've never broken</i>
<i>a blade as a bladesmith,</i>

28:11.771 --> 28:13.815
you haven't bladesmithed.

28:13.815 --> 28:15.400
<i>I have no regrets.</i>

28:15.400 --> 28:16.901
<i>This is merely</i>
<i>a stumbling block</i>

28:16.901 --> 28:18.736
<i>when you're</i>
<i>walking down the street.</i>

28:18.736 --> 28:20.321
You get up, you dust yourself
off, and you move on.

28:20.321 --> 28:22.282
<i>I came here to prove</i>
<i>that I can make a knife</i>

28:22.282 --> 28:24.284
<i>under strenuous conditions</i>
<i>in three hours.</i>

28:24.284 --> 28:25.368
<i>I did that.</i>

28:25.368 --> 28:28.580
Win or lose, I did that.

28:28.580 --> 28:30.415
- Bladesmiths, congratulations,

28:30.415 --> 28:32.959
you've made it to the final
round of this competition.

28:32.959 --> 28:34.878
Now we're sending
you back to your home forges

28:34.878 --> 28:37.172
to re-create
an iconic weapon from history.

28:37.172 --> 28:40.842
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:40.842 --> 28:42.218
The Kabyle Flyssa.

28:42.218 --> 28:44.596
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:44.596 --> 28:46.890
<i>Both functional and ornate,</i>

28:46.890 --> 28:49.267
<i>the Flyssa is the traditional</i>
<i>sword of the Kabyle Berbers</i>

28:49.267 --> 28:50.643
<i>of North Africa.</i>

28:50.643 --> 28:52.353
<i>Ranging in size from daggers</i>

28:52.353 --> 28:54.314
<i>to sabers over three feet</i>
<i>in length,</i>

28:54.314 --> 28:56.483
<i>Flyssas are single-edged,</i>
<i>a straight bank,</i>

28:56.483 --> 28:58.776
<i>and cutting edge that tapers.</i>

28:58.776 --> 29:01.696
<i>The long, needle-like tip and</i>
<i>unusual weight and balance</i>

29:01.696 --> 29:03.823
<i>make it ideal for tearing</i>
<i>through mail armor</i>

29:03.823 --> 29:06.451
<i>commonly worn throughout</i>
<i>the 19th century.</i>

29:06.451 --> 29:09.204
<i>The Flyssa was deeply rooted</i>
<i>in the Berber's faith,</i>

29:09.204 --> 29:11.956
<i>and is complete with</i>
<i>complex geometric designs</i>

29:11.956 --> 29:13.917
<i>and animal head pommel.</i>

29:13.917 --> 29:16.127
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:16.127 --> 29:18.505
The blade must be at least
two inches wide at the base,

29:18.505 --> 29:21.174
taper to a waist,
flare to a belly

29:21.174 --> 29:22.592
that's at least
two inches wide,

29:22.592 --> 29:24.594
and then taper again
to a point.

29:24.594 --> 29:30.183
You must also have an animal
icon head on your pommel.

29:30.183 --> 29:32.143
Bladesmiths, you will have
five days at your home forge

29:32.143 --> 29:33.686
to complete this challenge.

29:33.686 --> 29:35.146
At the end of five days,
you will return

29:35.146 --> 29:36.356
and present your weapons

29:36.356 --> 29:38.274
to our panel of expert judges.

29:38.274 --> 29:40.151
And only after
they've thoroughly tested them

29:40.151 --> 29:42.529
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion

29:42.529 --> 29:45.365
who also receives
a check for ten grand.

29:45.365 --> 29:47.367
Good luck.
We'll see you in five days.

29:47.367 --> 29:49.577
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:49.577 --> 29:52.497
- The Kabyle Flyssa
is really long.

29:52.497 --> 29:54.290
Way too long for this.

29:54.290 --> 29:57.001
I'm gonna have to cut
the hell out of my forge.

29:57.001 --> 29:59.337
<i>I feel kind of like</i>
<i>the suburban Ryu,</i>

29:59.337 --> 30:01.589
<i>'cause, you know,</i>
<i>I don't have a satellite dish.</i>

30:01.589 --> 30:04.175
<i>I kind of have</i>
<i>just a big fire pit</i>

30:04.175 --> 30:07.053
that is not great for forging.

30:07.053 --> 30:10.723
Ready to forge in fire?

30:10.723 --> 30:14.227
So this is my only piece of W1.

30:14.227 --> 30:16.479
And it should be plenty
of steel for the sword,

30:16.479 --> 30:18.982
but if I ruin it,
it's gonna be really difficult

30:18.982 --> 30:21.317
to replace.

30:21.317 --> 30:22.902
Oh, [bleep].
Got that a little too hot.

30:22.902 --> 30:24.821
[pounding]

30:24.821 --> 30:28.283
Might've left the steel
in a little too long.

30:28.283 --> 30:30.827
It got so hot
it started fracturing.

30:30.827 --> 30:33.454
If that blade burns,
then that's it, I'm done.

30:33.454 --> 30:35.957
<i>I wasted all that time.</i>
<i>I've got to be careful.</i>

30:35.957 --> 30:37.584
I'm never taking
my eyes off that baby.

30:37.584 --> 30:41.504
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:41.504 --> 30:43.548
<i>- I'm so happy to be back</i>
<i>to my home forge</i>

30:43.548 --> 30:45.300
<i>with my own tools.</i>

30:45.300 --> 30:47.176
<i>And I'm very excited</i>
<i>to get started</i>

30:47.176 --> 30:50.054
building this Flyssa sword.

30:50.054 --> 30:52.682
<i>I think that the biggest thing</i>
<i>that will slow me down</i>

30:52.682 --> 30:55.768
<i>with forging the blade is,</i>
<i>I use all hand tools</i>

30:55.768 --> 30:58.313
<i>and 18th century methods</i>
<i>to do all of my work.</i>

30:58.313 --> 31:00.356
<i>I don't have any hydraulic</i>
<i>presses, power hammers,</i>

31:00.356 --> 31:01.941
<i>or any of the above.</i>

31:01.941 --> 31:04.235
So, I've got a whole lot
of hammering to do.

31:04.235 --> 31:06.613
[clanging]

31:06.613 --> 31:09.282
<i>Steel being the super high</i>
<i>carbon steel like it is,</i>

31:09.282 --> 31:12.952
<i>it's not moving a whole lot,</i>
<i>even at a pretty high heat.</i>

31:12.952 --> 31:16.372
<i>So, I've got my work</i>
<i>cut out for me.</i>

31:16.372 --> 31:18.124
No doubt about it.

31:18.124 --> 31:20.543
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:20.543 --> 31:23.504
- So, first thing
I want to do is try

31:23.504 --> 31:24.631
to straighten
this puppy out.

31:24.631 --> 31:27.008
[fan whirring]

31:27.008 --> 31:29.010
<i>The good thing about today</i>
<i>compared to yesterday is,</i>

31:29.010 --> 31:32.180
<i>now the steel is flat</i>
<i>and thinned out a bunch,</i>

31:32.180 --> 31:34.015
it takes heat
a lot more quickly

31:34.015 --> 31:35.642
and it moves a lot easier.

31:35.642 --> 31:37.685
Working it is
going pretty smoothly.

31:37.685 --> 31:39.979
[pounding]

31:39.979 --> 31:42.231
I'm trying to get
to the two inches wide

31:42.231 --> 31:44.567
at the base of the
blade and at the belly,

31:44.567 --> 31:47.487
it's not fun.
It's getting extremely thin.

31:47.487 --> 31:50.156
And that has to be two inches
wide--those are the parameters.

31:50.156 --> 31:52.200
It's got me a little worried,
you know?

31:52.200 --> 31:54.827
An extremely thin blade is
gonna be prone

31:54.827 --> 31:56.704
to warp in the quench.

31:56.704 --> 31:58.414
[knocking]

31:58.414 --> 32:00.124
Can I trust you?

32:00.124 --> 32:03.044
Will you be my sword?

32:03.044 --> 32:04.504
Or will you fail me?

32:04.504 --> 32:06.297
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:06.297 --> 32:07.674
<i>- I feel like</i>
<i>I've gotten a lot done</i>

32:07.674 --> 32:09.425
<i>in the last couple of days.</i>

32:09.425 --> 32:10.301
<i>There's still a little bit</i>
<i>of polishing</i>

32:10.301 --> 32:11.719
<i>that I would like to do</i>

32:11.719 --> 32:13.054
before I can
call the blade done.

32:13.054 --> 32:15.014
[pounding]

32:15.014 --> 32:16.891
But the main thing that I do
have some concern about

32:16.891 --> 32:19.394
is the actual hardening
of the blade.

32:19.394 --> 32:22.230
I've definitely been putting
it off as long as possible

32:22.230 --> 32:24.190
because it could
either warp on me,

32:24.190 --> 32:25.692
it could get
a crack in the blade.

32:25.692 --> 32:30.488
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:30.488 --> 32:33.116
<i>Listening for that ping.</i>

32:33.116 --> 32:34.867
Trying to make sure
that it stayed straight.

32:34.867 --> 32:36.994
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:36.994 --> 32:40.540
It's definitely not
as straight as I was hoping.

32:40.540 --> 32:43.209
And there's no way to fix that.

32:43.209 --> 32:44.836
So, we're gonna roll with it.

32:44.836 --> 32:46.254
We're moving on.

32:46.254 --> 32:48.798
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:48.798 --> 32:51.551
- I'm digging
a freaking trench.

32:51.551 --> 32:53.344
This is what happens
when you just have

32:53.344 --> 32:55.304
an old fire pit as a forge,

32:55.304 --> 32:57.306
and when you're poor.

32:57.306 --> 33:00.226
You know, you can't afford
the nice, long forges.

33:00.226 --> 33:02.270
<i>It's kind of do or die today.</i>

33:02.270 --> 33:04.647
I've got to get this thing
heat treated as fast as I can.

33:04.647 --> 33:07.608
This is a quench trench.
You know what I'm saying?

33:07.608 --> 33:10.361
It's a trench
so that I can quench.

33:10.361 --> 33:12.947
<i>If it goes poorly,</i>
<i>then I'm really up the creek.</i>

33:12.947 --> 33:16.743
And you might see a grown man
freak out on national TV.

33:16.743 --> 33:20.663
There is very little precision
in what's happening right now.

33:20.663 --> 33:22.790
This has to work.
If it doesn't work,

33:22.790 --> 33:26.085
I'm just done,
I'm out, I'm finished.

33:26.085 --> 33:28.436
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:31.378 --> 33:32.543
- Make swords, they said.

33:32.543 --> 33:35.338
It'll be fun!

33:35.338 --> 33:37.131
<i>I'm gonna attempt</i>
<i>a vertical quench,</i>

33:37.131 --> 33:39.508
because that should keep
the blade from warping.

33:39.508 --> 33:41.552
<i>If I went in for</i>
<i>a horizontal quench,</i>

33:41.552 --> 33:42.887
then there's a chance,
you know,

33:42.887 --> 33:44.555
just the weight of itself

33:44.555 --> 33:46.307
would start to pull it
and bend it.

33:46.307 --> 33:47.975
<i>So, if you're holding</i>
<i>it vertically,</i>

33:47.975 --> 33:50.061
<i>there's a better chance</i>
<i>it'll stay straight.</i>

33:50.061 --> 33:53.856
[grunts]
Razzle dazzle, baby.

33:53.856 --> 33:56.984
I'm fully expecting this thing
to be all warped and crazy,

33:56.984 --> 33:59.320
and it's straight.

33:59.320 --> 34:03.658
The verdict right now is...
[breathing heavily]

34:03.658 --> 34:06.410
Is I'm really tired.
That's the verdict.

34:06.410 --> 34:08.537
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

34:08.537 --> 34:11.499
- I hammered a dragon head out
on the end of this blade.

34:11.499 --> 34:14.794
I didn't like the way that the
dragon head turned out so much.

34:14.794 --> 34:16.087
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:16.087 --> 34:18.005
Boom.

34:18.005 --> 34:19.924
So I decided I'm gonna do,
I think, an eagle's head

34:19.924 --> 34:22.093
with my handle material,

34:22.093 --> 34:24.303
<i>instead of part</i>
<i>of the blade material.</i>

34:24.303 --> 34:26.806
<i>It's gonna cut a little bit</i>
<i>more weight off of the sword,</i>

34:26.806 --> 34:30.226
<i>which will be a good thing, so</i>
<i>it may work out in my favor.</i>

34:30.226 --> 34:32.728
I can see the eagle head
inside this chunk of wood,

34:32.728 --> 34:34.980
so I'm excited
to make it happen.

34:34.980 --> 34:37.233
The handle section,
it does seem very small

34:37.233 --> 34:39.652
<i>for the size of the sword,</i>
<i>but we're trying to stick</i>

34:39.652 --> 34:41.445
<i>close to the original.</i>

34:41.445 --> 34:44.031
<i>It's definitely</i>
<i>a knife handle on a sword,</i>

34:44.031 --> 34:46.534
<i>but I put a nice</i>
<i>pom swell in there.</i>

34:46.534 --> 34:47.618
<i>I think</i>
<i>that's gonna help a lot</i>

34:47.618 --> 34:49.453
<i>with the grip on the sword.</i>

34:49.453 --> 34:51.956
I'm confident that the handle
will work out well.

34:51.956 --> 34:55.584
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:55.584 --> 34:57.294
- Bladesmiths,
welcome back to The Forge.

34:57.294 --> 34:58.671
Collin, how did it go?

34:58.671 --> 35:01.048
<i>- W1 blade, cable Damascus,</i>

35:01.048 --> 35:03.676
<i>bolsters, and pommel.</i>
<i>African blackwood handle,</i>

35:03.676 --> 35:05.886
and you'll have to guess
the animal head.

35:05.886 --> 35:08.055
[laughter]

35:08.055 --> 35:10.016
- Daniel, tell the judges
about your blade.

35:11.183 --> 35:13.060
<i>- I feel like</i>
<i>it went pretty well.</i>

35:13.060 --> 35:15.062
I went with an eagle's head
carved out of birdseye maple.

35:15.062 --> 35:17.314
<i>Did a little bit of geometric</i>
<i>design on the blade.</i>

35:17.314 --> 35:18.983
<i>I feel like I did</i>
<i>the absolute best I could</i>

35:18.983 --> 35:20.818
in the time that I had,
so I'm happy.

35:20.818 --> 35:23.988
- Well, gentlemen, looks are
secondary to performance.

35:23.988 --> 35:26.115
And now it's time to see how
your blades perform

35:26.115 --> 35:27.450
in our weapons test.

35:27.450 --> 35:29.827
Up first, the kill test.
Doug?

35:29.827 --> 35:32.329
- To see what kind of lethal
damage your weapon will do,

35:32.329 --> 35:33.748
I'll deliver
slashes and thrusts

35:33.748 --> 35:34.707
on this ballistics dummy.

35:34.707 --> 35:36.292
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:36.292 --> 35:37.543
Collin, you're up first.
You ready?

35:37.543 --> 35:39.128
- Have fun.
- Let's do this.

35:39.128 --> 35:41.422
To help me today,
I'm bringing back

35:41.422 --> 35:43.758
one of Marcaida Kali's
chief instructors.

35:43.758 --> 35:46.886
Please welcome
US Staff Sergeant Chris Mask.

35:46.886 --> 35:49.055
- After the failure in
round two, I'm hesitant to say

35:49.055 --> 35:50.806
that my sword
is gonna be awesome.

35:50.806 --> 35:52.641
I want to see
what my sword does,

35:52.641 --> 35:54.310
and only then
will I fell better

35:54.310 --> 35:57.104
about my mistakes
in round two.

35:57.104 --> 36:03.986
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:09.075 --> 36:15.998
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:19.210 --> 36:21.087
[laughs]

36:21.087 --> 36:22.129
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:22.129 --> 36:23.506
- All right, Collin.

36:23.506 --> 36:26.258
Your Kabyle Flyssa
is very sharp.

36:26.258 --> 36:29.887
On the initial thrust,
it penetrated deep and easily

36:29.887 --> 36:31.889
through this whole
ballistics dummy.

36:31.889 --> 36:33.432
The handle is comfortable.

36:33.432 --> 36:35.726
It's easy to slash in
and thrust out.

36:35.726 --> 36:39.772
Overall, it will kill.
Good job.

36:39.772 --> 36:41.273
- Thank you, sir.

36:41.273 --> 36:42.566
- All right, Daniel, your turn.
You ready?

36:42.566 --> 36:44.693
- Yes, sir.
- Let's do this.

36:44.693 --> 36:46.654
<i>- I'm feeling a little nervous</i>
<i>about the kill test.</i>

36:46.654 --> 36:49.323
Win or lose, I just hope
my sword doesn't break.

36:49.323 --> 36:56.205
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:05.965 --> 37:09.218
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:09.218 --> 37:10.928
[laughter]

37:10.928 --> 37:15.516
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:15.516 --> 37:17.685
- [laughs]
- All right, Daniel,

37:17.685 --> 37:20.855
your weapon is wicked sharp.

37:20.855 --> 37:23.732
On the initial thrust,
it penetrated deep,

37:23.732 --> 37:25.609
and on the way out,
with your belly being forward,

37:25.609 --> 37:28.154
it lacerates out easily.

37:28.154 --> 37:31.699
Now, because you have
such a very skinny handle

37:31.699 --> 37:34.702
right here, right, there's
no pommel with a counterweight.

37:34.702 --> 37:36.412
All the weight is in front.

37:36.412 --> 37:38.956
The balance just makes
the blade rotate

37:38.956 --> 37:40.624
with a small handle
like this.

37:40.624 --> 37:43.961
But in terms of damage,
it will kill.

37:43.961 --> 37:45.963
- Thank you.
- Good job.

37:45.963 --> 37:48.841
- All right, bladesmiths, next
up is the strength test. Ben?

37:48.841 --> 37:50.885
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:50.885 --> 37:52.887
- Bladesmiths, to test
the strength and durability

37:52.887 --> 37:55.097
of your Kabyle Flyssa,
I'll be smashing them

37:55.097 --> 37:56.724
into these terra cotta pots
edge first.

37:56.724 --> 37:58.058
Remember,
this test is all about

37:58.058 --> 37:59.476
what the pots do
to your blades,

37:59.476 --> 38:00.853
and not what
the blades do to the pots.

38:00.853 --> 38:02.062
Collin, you're up first.
You ready?

38:02.062 --> 38:03.397
- Yes, sir.
- All right.

38:03.397 --> 38:10.362
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:13.490 --> 38:14.491
- Awesome, man.

38:14.491 --> 38:15.910
- [exhales]

38:15.910 --> 38:19.496
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:19.496 --> 38:21.165
- Well, Collin, your blade
held up beautifully.

38:21.165 --> 38:24.293
The edge, it's like it never
saw the terra cotta.

38:24.293 --> 38:25.711
You did a great job.
Well done.

38:25.711 --> 38:27.046
- Thank you, sir.

38:27.046 --> 38:27.963
- Daniel, you're up.
You ready?

38:27.963 --> 38:28.923
- I'm ready.

38:28.923 --> 38:35.930
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:41.894 --> 38:46.190
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:46.190 --> 38:48.359
- Well, Daniel,
your edge held up pretty well.

38:48.359 --> 38:49.985
If I run my fingers across,
I can feel

38:49.985 --> 38:51.946
just a little bit
of a wire edge.

38:51.946 --> 38:53.739
But nothing major.

38:53.739 --> 38:56.951
But my big concern...
this handle.

38:56.951 --> 38:58.869
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:58.869 --> 39:01.956
It's so small that
I had a tough time indexing it.

39:01.956 --> 39:03.749
But it's beautifully carved,
edge held up beautifully.

39:03.749 --> 39:04.792
Very well done.

39:04.792 --> 39:05.960
- Thank you, sir.

39:05.960 --> 39:07.962
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:07.962 --> 39:10.172
- All right, gentlemen,
you survived our kill test

39:10.172 --> 39:11.340
and our strength test.

39:11.340 --> 39:13.133
Now the sharpness test.

39:13.133 --> 39:14.677
To test the sharpness
of that blade

39:14.677 --> 39:16.262
and to see if it still
has an edge,

39:16.262 --> 39:18.389
I'll be cutting
through these fish.

39:18.389 --> 39:21.600
A clean, sharp blade should
pass right through those fish.

39:21.600 --> 39:23.686
With a dull blade,
it's gonna knock those fish

39:23.686 --> 39:26.063
out of the way, or give us
a jagged, torn cut.

39:26.063 --> 39:27.231
- Collin, you ready?

39:27.231 --> 39:28.774
- Yes, sir.
- Okay.

39:28.774 --> 39:31.110
- Dave Baker's about
to wield my sword.

39:31.110 --> 39:34.321
That alone is you know,
worth 1,000 points.

39:34.321 --> 39:37.574
But I'm just thinking, "Please
just slice through this thing."

39:37.574 --> 39:40.308
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:42.779 --> 39:44.448
- Collin, you ready?
- Yes, sir.

39:44.448 --> 39:45.908
- Okay.
<i>- I'm just thinking,</i>

39:45.908 --> 39:49.620
please just slice
through this thing.

39:49.620 --> 39:56.585
<i>[drama ♪ ♪</i>

40:04.593 --> 40:10.098
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:10.098 --> 40:12.684
- All right, Collin, right off,
it's definitely a sharp blade.

40:12.684 --> 40:14.269
It cut very nicely.

40:14.269 --> 40:18.023
Your handle is
a bit on the fat side.

40:18.023 --> 40:19.691
But it's definitely a cutter.

40:19.691 --> 40:21.068
Good job.
- Thank you, sir.

40:21.068 --> 40:22.527
- Daniel, are you ready?
- Yes.

40:22.527 --> 40:24.321
- Okay, great.

40:24.321 --> 40:26.990
- I feel that Collin and I
are still neck and neck.

40:26.990 --> 40:29.493
<i>I think that I've got</i>
<i>a good edge on him.</i>

40:29.493 --> 40:32.287
But all you can do is hope
for the best at this point.

40:32.287 --> 40:39.211
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:46.760 --> 40:47.970
- Mm.

40:47.970 --> 40:50.472
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:50.472 --> 40:54.184
- All right, Daniel.
This blade is wicked sharp.

40:54.184 --> 40:56.103
And those cuts--you can see,

40:56.103 --> 40:58.146
they just blew
right through the fish.

40:58.146 --> 41:02.109
My problem is.
this is so small,

41:02.109 --> 41:03.902
I had to fight to keep it
in my hand.

41:03.902 --> 41:06.154
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:06.154 --> 41:09.741
These Flyssa often have
a very small handle.

41:09.741 --> 41:12.452
But what saves that
is having that pommel

41:12.452 --> 41:16.707
keeping your hand from coming
off the back of that blade.

41:16.707 --> 41:19.459
It's an amazing cutter.
It's just very difficult

41:19.459 --> 41:20.585
to hold on to.

41:20.585 --> 41:24.256
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:24.256 --> 41:26.258
- Daniel, Collin,
there can only be one

41:26.258 --> 41:28.010
"Forged in Fire" champion.

41:28.010 --> 41:29.261
And that champion is...

41:29.261 --> 41:34.683
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:34.683 --> 41:36.768
Collin.
Congratulations,

41:36.768 --> 41:39.104
you are our new
"Forged in Fire" champion.

41:39.104 --> 41:42.149
Daniel, your sword
didn't make the cut.

41:42.149 --> 41:44.067
- Daniel, you gave us
a beautiful blade

41:44.067 --> 41:45.944
and a beautiful handle.

41:45.944 --> 41:47.821
Unfortunately, you made
a weapon that we all agree

41:47.821 --> 41:49.906
was difficult to control.

41:49.906 --> 41:51.783
So that balance,
that small handle,

41:51.783 --> 41:54.328
it made a weapon
that couldn't be used at speed,

41:54.328 --> 41:55.787
at full force.

41:55.787 --> 41:57.414
That's why
we're letting you go.

41:57.414 --> 42:00.667
- Daniel,
please surrender your blade.

42:00.667 --> 42:02.794
- I am disappointed, of course,
that I didn't win.

42:02.794 --> 42:05.922
But I'm absolutely proud
of the work I did here.

42:05.922 --> 42:08.675
If anything, I think that this
fuels my fire to work harder

42:08.675 --> 42:10.844
and do better.

42:10.844 --> 42:12.679
- Collin, congratulations,
you are

42:12.679 --> 42:14.806
our new "Forged in Fire"
champion

42:14.806 --> 42:16.141
and that's a title that comes
with a check for ten grand.

42:16.141 --> 42:17.726
Good job, buddy.
[applause]

42:17.726 --> 42:19.561
And as far as
your animal head pommel,

42:19.561 --> 42:22.022
I'm gonna go ahead and say
it's probably an underdog.

42:22.022 --> 42:24.316
[laughter]

42:24.316 --> 42:28.779
- Well, Collin, please present
your weapon to the judges.

42:28.779 --> 42:32.657
<i>- Wil Willis out here</i>
<i>telling me I'm a champion?</i>

42:32.657 --> 42:34.493
Can you believe it?

42:34.493 --> 42:36.536
Mmm!

42:36.536 --> 42:39.623
<i>The champ.</i>
<i>I can't believe it.</i>

42:39.623 --> 42:42.834
"Forged in Fire"
champion out here!

42:42.834 --> 42:44.961
Ooh!

42:44.961 --> 42:49.216
<i>♪ ♪</i>
